label("$13$",(A+B)/2,NE);
label("$12$",(B+C)/2,SE);
label("$5$",(A+C)/2,W);
label("$4$",(C+M)/2,W);
label("$4$",(C+N)/2,S);
[/asy]

Since $MJ$ and $NK$ are perpendicular to $AB$, we see that quadrilaterals $CMJK$ and $CNKJ$ are both trapezoids.  The height of each trapezoid is the length of the altitude from $C$ to $\overline{AB}$.  This altitude divides triangle $ABC$ into two right triangles, and we can use the Pythagorean Theorem to find its length: \[\sqrt{5^2-3^2} = 4.\]

[asy]
pair A,B,C,N,K,M,J;
A=(0,5);
B=(12,0);
C=(0,0);
N=(5,0);
M=(0,4);
J=(0.35,4.84);
K=(6,2.4);
draw(A--B--C--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
draw(N--K,linewidth(0.7));
draw(M--J,linewidth(0.7));
draw(C--(3,0),dashed,linewidth(0.7));
label("$A$",A,NW);
label("$M$",M,W);
label("$C$",C,SW);
label("$N$",N,S);
label("$B$",B,SE);
label("$K$",K,NE);
label("$J$",J,NE);
label("$13$",(A+B)/2,NE);
label("$12$",(B+C)/2,SE);
label("$5$",(A+C)/2,W);
label("$4$",(C+M)/2,W);
label("$4$",(C+N)/2,S);
label("$4$",(C+(3,0))/2,S);
label("$3$",(3,0)/2,S);
[/asy]

The area of trapezoid $CMJK$ is \[\frac{1}{2}(4+CM)(4) = \frac{1}{2}(8)(4)=16.\]The area of trapezoid $CNKJ$ is \[\frac{1}{2}(4+CN)(4) = \frac{1}{2}(8)(4)=16.\]

Finally, the area of pentagon $CMJKN$ is the sum of the areas of triangles $CMN$ and $CMJK$ and $CNKJ$, or \[\frac{96}{5}+16+16 = \frac{208}{5}.\]Final Answer: $\boxed{\frac{208}{5}}$. I hope it is correct.

